Okay, assuming I've understood your question correctly, here you go.

To convert the function to an arrow function you would just write it like so:

const toggleMenu = () => {
  if (!showMenu) {
      hamburger.classList.add("open");
      showMenu = true;
    } else {
      hamburger.classList.remove("open");
      showMenu = false;
    }
}

Where you might be getting an error, although I can't be sure without seeing your code, is you might have forgotten to then move your event listener to after the function expression. Function expressions aren't hoisted like function declarations are so you cannot call them before expressing them.

As per the usage of a ternary operator, I'm not exactly sure why you would want to in this case. You don't typically (or ever?) want to utilize ternaries for side-effects - only for expressions (something that returns a value). That being said, you could use an IIFE (immediately invoked function expression) to get done what you want but it's just more confusing IMO. 
Here is a way to do it:

const toggleMenu = () => {
    showMenu = showMenu
      ? (() => {
          hamburger.classList.remove("open");
          return false;
        })()
      : (() => {
          hamburger.classList.add("open");
          return true;
        })();
}

Happy to help further if I've completely misunderstood what you're getting after!

